                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d460">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.82/75a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hibbard</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-06-11T23:00:00-04:00"
                            >June 11, 1942—11 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>179. I should appreciate it if President Barclay would set aside sufficient time
                    in these critical days to discuss with you personally whatever important matters
                    may be pending in the relations between our two countries. I feel that in order
                    successfully to carry out the mutual tasks which lie before us, it is essential
                    to maintain the closest possible contact and to advise and consult on all phases
                    of developments now taking place.</p>
                <pb facs="0392" n="380" xml:id="pg_380"/>
                <p>I should also be glad to receive frequent and detailed telegraphic reports from
                    your office as to the progress of our operations in Liberia.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
